    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1957-05-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1957-05-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="46"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d46">
                <head>46. Memorandum of a Conversation, Department of State, Washington, May 21,
                        1957<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d46fn1">Source: Department of State,
                        Secretary’s Memoranda of Conversation: Lot 64 D 199. Secret. Drafted by
                            <persName corresp="#p_ECB1">Elbrick</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <hi rend="italic">
                            <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                                type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1957-05-21">May 21,
                                1957</date>
                        </hi>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>French Government Crisis</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>Foreign Minister <persName corresp="#p_PC1">Pineau</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_AH1">Alphand</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>The Secretary</item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_DCD1">Dillon</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_ECB1">Elbrick</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_VJ1">Vimont</persName>, Minister, French
                        Embassy</item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName>de Laboulaye</persName>, Counselor, French Embassy</item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_WWNJ1">Walmsley</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <pb facs="0165" n="127" xml:id="pg_127"/>
                <p>During his call at the Department today <persName corresp="#p_PC1"
                        >Pineau</persName>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d46fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_PC1">Pineau</persName> arrived in New York on May 19
                        and attended a meeting of the U.N. Security Council on May 20. Regarding his
                        conversation on the Suez Canal question with Secretary <persName
                            corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName>, May 21, see <ref
                            target="frus1955-57v17#pg_624">vol. XVII, p. 624</ref>.</note> was asked
                    by the Secretary what result could be expected from the vote of confidence to
                    take place this evening in the Assembly in Paris.<note n="3" xml:id="d46fn3">The
                            <persName corresp="#p_MG3">Mollet</persName> government was defeated in
                        the National Assembly on a bill to increase taxation on May 21 and resigned.
                        Three weeks later, on June 11, <persName corresp="#p_BMM1"
                            >Bourgès-Maunoury</persName> succeeded in forming a Cabinet in which
                            <persName corresp="#p_PC1">Pineau</persName> was Foreign Minister.
                        Reports on this Ministerial crisis are in Department of State, Central File
                        751.00.</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_PC1">Pineau</persName> said that there was some hope that
                    the Government would survive, particularly in view of the fact that its
                    budgetary plans now called for a diminution of the budget by 400 billion francs.
                    He said that this was the first time that such a reduction had occurred and
                    should be a favorable factor. The Secretary remarked that it was feared that any
                    change of government at this time in France might have an adverse effect on the
                    prospects for ratification of the Common Market and <gloss target="#t_EURATOM1"
                        >EURATOM</gloss> Treaties. <persName corresp="#p_PC1">Pineau</persName>
                    agreed. He said that it should be possible to ratify the treaties before the
                    summer recess of Parliament if the Government remains in power.<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d46fn4">The bill authorizing President Coty to sign the treaties
                        passed in the National Assembly on July 9 and in the Council of the Republic
                        on July 24.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
